Data-driven Retention Insights for HR in Manufacturing¶

Executive Summary:¶

Background:

The HR department at an anonymous vehicle manufacturer has enlisted public assistance to improve employee retention by leveraging data science and machine learning for identifying drivers of churn (16.6% at time of writing) - citing the time and expenses consumed to find, interview, and hire new employees.

Stakeholders posited that a known high occupational injury rate would be the main driver for employee turnover and termination, as indicated by a 2019 study in the International journal of environmental research and public health and supported by a 2020 study by the Indonesia ministry of manpower that put fatal accidents at 40 per 100k workers and other accidents at 1430 per 100k workers.

Findings: Statistical Analysis¶

There were satistically significant differences between churned and retained employee satisfaction, numbers of projects, average tenure, accident rate, and promotion rate.

Initial correlation analysis indicated the positive influence of higher salaries (0.12) and work satisfaction (0.35) as well as the negative influence of being overworked (0.13). In fact, 36.1% of employees worked more than 225 hours per month.There were other notable observations. Since eventually everyone churns, if not only due to retirement, the positive correlation between longer tenure and churn is unsurprizing.

However, the puzzling positive (0.13) correlation discovered between workplace accidents and retention implied those who enduced an occupational injury were more likely to stay. The data revealed a 15.4% accident rate - nearly 10 times the national average of 1.4%; thus, this class balance suggests that the pattern within work_accident could not be due to an input error - as a 84.5% accident rate is implausible.

Findings: Machine Learning Model¶

Out of the three models used, the XGBoost classifier reported the highest recall score ($0.920/1.000$); recall score was chosen to maximize the likelihood of identifying employees likely to churn.

The complex interplay between satisfaction level, number of projects, last evaluations and average hours formed the basis for most of the model's predictions (as examined through $shap$ values) - with satisfaction_level as the most impactful ($-4.240<shap<6.313$) and statistically different ($p-value 1.19e-228$) for churned employees. Other, less impactful features included tenure_years, salary, and average hours (average_hrs_month). Despite from initial expectations, workplace accidents (work_accident) were not shown to be strongly influential ($1.338<shap<0.186$).

Recommendations & Insights:¶

From the factors presented in the Findings, by establishing monitoring policies these factors and their threshold recommendations, it is possible to intervene on 94.2% of churned employees.

  • Satisfaction Level: Satisfaction below 0.47, especially below 0.12, should be prioritized. While 100% of employees below satisfaction level 0.12 will churn (25.1% of churn), satisfaction below 0.47 accounted for 70.5% of churned employees, with 49.2% likelihood to churn for any employee.

  • Tenure: The most important years are 3 to 6, especially employees within 4th and 5th years, as 98.4% of churn occurs within 3-6 years of tenure. In addition, any employees of 7+ years (0% of churn) or less than 2 (1.6% of churn) are not an immediate priority. Even though 43.8% of churn occurs in year 3, the chance of churn within year 3 is only 16.8%, whereas years 4 and 5, together accounting for 49.1% of churn, have a risk of 24.7% and 45.4% respectively.

  • Number of Projects: Employee project load should be examined. Any employees handling 7 projects will churn (7.3% of churn). The safe zone is within 3-5 projects (6.6% risk of churn), outside of which (2 or 6+) employees have a 53.8% likelihood to churn (69.0% of churn).

  • Average Monthly Hours: Work hours similarly contain areas of danger. Any employee with more than 287hrs will churn (9.24% of churn). There are two at-risk ranges : 1) 126 to 162hr range and 2) 226 to 310hr range, accounting for 43.7% and 49.0% of churn respectively (total 92.7%). There are areas with reliably lower churn. The "safe zone" is below 126hrs with 0% churn and the "optimal zone" is 146 to 226 hrs, within which only 8.4% churn occurs.

  • Last Evaluation: The evaluation system might incentivize employees towards unsustainable work patterns. Last evaluation score is correlated negatively with churn and positively with average hours per month. 87.5% of churn occurs outside of the 0.6 to 0.8 evaluation range. Low scores (below 0.6) lead to churn (26.9% risk of churn), while higher scores (0.8+) also drive churn (21.2% risk of churn).

Conclusions:¶

The XGBoost Classifier uncovered a number of indicators that clearly drive churn and can be reliably monitored to intervene in situations of churn. The model can be deloyed live to assist the use of dashboards focusing on the indicators of satisfaction, tenure, projects, monthly hours, and recent evaluations to ensure a maximum chance of intervention. In addition, improvement to the factors that drive these indicators, though an evaluation system overhaul, overwork prevention measures, improvements to work satisfaction. Analysis of a public HR dataset suggested drivers of satifaction, the main indicator, include salary, positive performance ratings, and distance from home.

Dataset Dictionary¶

Variable Description
left Outcome, Whether or not the employee left the company
satisfaction_level Employee-reported job satisfaction level [0–1]
last_evaluation Score of employee's last performance review [0–1]
number_project Number of projects employee contributes to
average_monthly_hours Average number of hours employee worked per month
time_spend_company How long the employee has been with the company (years)
Work_accident Whether or not the employee experienced an accident while at work
promotion_last_5years Whether or not the employee was promoted in the last 5 years
Department The employee's department
salary The employee's salary category (10k Indonesia rupiah)

for col in df_.columns:
    
    data = df_[col]
    if data.value_counts().count() > 2 and data.dtype!="O":
        iqr = data.quantile(.75) - data.quantile(.25)
        upper_lim = data.quantile(.75) + iqr * 1.5 
        lower_lim = data.quantile(.25) - iqr * 1.5
        outliers = ((data<=lower_lim)|(data>=upper_lim)).sum()
        # export outlier data?
        #outliers_df = data[data > lower_lim & data < upper_lim]

Helper Function: V/HLines

In [17]:
def set_line_at(val,orient):
    if orient=="h":
        left, right = plt.xlim()
        plt.hlines(val,xmin=left,xmax=right,colors="grey",linestyles="dashed",alpha=0.3)
        plt.xlim(left,right)
    elif orient=="v":
        top, bot = plt.ylim()
        plt.vlines(val,ymin=bot,ymax=top,colors="grey",linestyles="dashed",alpha=0.3)
        plt.ylim(top,bot)
    else:
        raise TypeError(f"{orient} must be h or v.")

Helper Function: Hypothesis Testing¶

In [25]:
def hypocheck(col_list,aliases,df_a,df_b):
    col_alias= {col:alias for (col,alias) in zip(col_list,aliases)}
    for col in col_list:
        pval=stats.ttest_ind(
            a=df_a[col],
            b=df_b[col],
            equal_var=False
            )[1]
        print(f"It is {str(pval<0.05).lower()} (at p-value {pval:.3}) that {col_alias[col]} differs between employees who churned and not.\n")

#make data split
def split_data(X,y):
    x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,train_size=0.6,random_state=42,stratify=y)
    x_test,x_val,y_test,y_val=train_test_split(x_test,y_test,train_size=0.5,random_state=42,stratify=y_test)
    for i in [x_train,x_val,x_test]:
        print(i.shape)
    print(X.shape,"\n",X.columns.tolist())
    return x_train,x_val,x_test,y_train,y_val,y_test

# training or loading for efficiency
def train_or_load(model,model_name,x_train,y_train):
    model_path = model_name + ".pickle"
    if os.path.exists(model_path):
        with open(model_path, 'rb') as to_read:
            model = pkl.load(to_read)
    else:
        model.fit(x_train,y_train)
        with open(model_path, 'wb') as to_write:
            pkl.dump(model, to_write) 
    return model

Evaluate Model Performance¶

In [40]:
def get_metric_name(metric):
    return f"{metric}".split("=")[0].replace("<function","").split("at")[0].strip()
In [41]:
def eval_model(model,model_name,results_df=pd.DataFrame(),show_cm=False):
    """
    Takes a model, its name/description, and a dataframe.
    Returns a dataframe with evaulation results, option to display a confusion matrix.
    """
    eval_results = {}
    eval_results["model_name"] = model_name
    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
    for metric in [metrics.accuracy_score,metrics.precision_score,metrics.recall_score,metrics.f1_score]:
            eval_results[get_metric_name(metric)]=[round(metric(y_test,y_pred),3)]
    if show_cm:
        cm= metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred,labels=model.classes_)
        disp= metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm,display_labels=model.classes_)
        disp.plot()   
        plt.title(f"{model_name} Confusion Matrix")
        plt.show()
    return pd.concat([results_df,pd.DataFrame(eval_results)],axis=0)

Helper Functions¶

In [252]:
def pop_within_param(upper_thres,lower_thres,indicator,inside=True):
    print(f"{snake_to_title(indicator)} within {lower_thres} to {upper_thres}:")

    total_pop = 0
    for df in [df_stay,df_left]:
        if inside == True:
            ppop = df[(df[indicator] < upper_thres) & (df[indicator] > lower_thres)]["churned"].count()
        else: 
            ppop = df[(df[indicator] > upper_thres) | (df[indicator] < lower_thres)]["churned"].count()
        per_pop = ppop/df.shape[0]
        print(per_pop,",", ppop,"of",df.shape[0])
        total_pop += ppop
        total_sample = ppop
    tpop = total_sample/total_pop
    print("total churned in sample: ",tpop,",",total_sample,"of",total_pop)
    return tpop

Cleaning: Reformating column names, values¶

In [173]:
def add_spacing(s):
    new_str = ""
    for ind,ss in enumerate(s):
        if ss.isupper() and ind > 0:
            new_str += " " + ss
        else:
            new_str += ss
    return new_str
In [174]:

corr_mat = ibm_att.corr(numeric_only=True)["Churn"]
droplist = []
corr_threshold = 0.04
for ind,x in corr_mat.items():
    if not (x > corr_threshold or x < -corr_threshold):
        droplist.append(ind)
corr_mat.drop(droplist+["Churn"],axis=0,inplace=True)
corr_mat.sort_values(inplace=True,ascending=False)
sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(corr_mat),annot=True,fmt=".2f",cmap="coolwarm")
plt.title(f"Churn Correlation within Public Dataset\n(Negative = Reduced churn)")
plt.show()

indicator = "Job Satisfaction"
for i in range(2):
    corr_mat = ibm_att[ibm_att["Churn"]==i].corr(numeric_only=True)[indicator]
    droplist = []
    corr_threshold = 0.01
    for ind,x in corr_mat.items():
        if not (x > corr_threshold or x < -corr_threshold):
            droplist.append(ind)
    corr_mat.drop(droplist+[indicator],axis=0,inplace=True)
    corr_mat.sort_values(inplace=True,ascending=False)
    sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(corr_mat),annot=True,fmt=".2f",cmap="coolwarm")

    plt.show()
